===Etymology===
{{OE.}} {{term|broþor|brōþor}}, from {{PG.}} *{{term||brōþēr}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|bʰréh₂tēr}}.  Cognates include Dutch {{term|broeder}}, German {{term|Bruder}}, and Danish & Swedish {{term|broder}}, all from the same Germanic root; and from Indo-European, Latin {{term|frater}}, Common Slavic *{{term|Appendix:Proto-Slavic *bratrъ|bratrъ}} (Russian {{term|sc=Cyrl|брат||tr=brat}}), Ancient Greek {{term|φράτηρ||tr=frater|sc=polytonic}}, Latvian {{term|brãlis}}, Persian {{term|برادر||tr=barâdar|sc=FAchar}}, Old Prussian {{term|brāti}}, and Welsh {{term|brawd}}.

